[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Root Cause
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m When a `MultiPart` is constructed in-process (as a client would build it for sending), each `BodyPart` stores the raw Java object passed to its constructor directly as its entity. Here that object is `byte[]`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m On the server side, Jersey's `com.sun.jersey.multipart.impl.MultiPartReader` (a `MessageBodyReader<MultiPart>`) deserialises the HTTP wire bytes and wraps each part's content in a `BodyPartEntity` that exposes an `InputStream`. That HTTP serialise-then-parse round-trip never occurs in a plain unit test. The test constructs the `MultiPart` the same way the client does, so the entity is still `byte[]` when the production cast runs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Two failure modes result:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Attempt | Code | Exception |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |---|---|---|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Direct cast | `(BodyPartEntity) bodyPart.getEntity()` | `ClassCastException: class [B cannot be cast to class com.sun.jersey.multipart.BodyPartEntity` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | `getEntityAs` fallback | `bodyPart.getEntityAs(BodyPartEntity.class)` | `IllegalStateException: Entity instance does not contain the unconverted content` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m `getEntityAs` requires the entity to be stored as raw bytes (the "unconverted" wire form), which is only true after `MessageBodyReader` has parsed the stream. Neither path works when the entity was set as a typed Java object.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
